  "prompt": "Is there a consensus that money laundering is against the law?",
  "response": "Yes, there is a strong and widespread consensus that money laundering is against the law. Money laundering is universally recognized as a criminal activity in most jurisdictions around the world. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal (or \"clean\") by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions.\n\nMost countries have enacted laws and regulations to combat money laundering. These laws are often in line with international standards set by organizations such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), which is a global watchdog for preventing money laundering and terrorist financing. The FATF provides recommendations that are widely adopted by its member countries to establish legal frameworks against money laundering.\n\nIn the United States, for example, the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) and the USA PATRIOT Act are key pieces of legislation that target money laundering activities. Similarly, the European Union has its own set of anti-money laundering directives that member states are required to implement into their national laws.\n\nThe reasons for criminalizing money laundering include its close association with other serious crimes such as drug trafficking, terrorism, corruption, and organized crime. By disrupting the financial incentives of these illegal activities, states aim to deter crime and maintain the integrity of their financial systems.\n\nTherefore, not only is there a consensus that money laundering is illegal, but there are also concerted international efforts to prevent, detect, and prosecute money laundering activities.",
